-1 just to flag that I think we need to talk through the CI bits.'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-10-30 03:11:02.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

We had some great feedback in the unconference.

Two key points were made.
1) We need our CI up and running for a period of time (not fully defined) before we propose integration
2) Demonstrate 'usage'.  This includes, but is not limited to, external reviewers, operators using the driver (though don't need specific names), or external contributions.

There was additional concern in the unconference from some of the cores about, when that is ready, who will review it?

However, given the first two items are pressing, the PowerVM drivers team is going to take these TODOs to go work.  We hope to sync back up at the mid-cycle meetup.

We also had prepped a Docs blue print, given Michael's feedback.  But given it was clear this blueprint would not be approved, the docs blueprint wasn't submitted yet.  However, one thought was perhaps we should get a head start on the docs.  I'm going to meet up with Lana and see if there is an opportunity to help create some docs around this driver (even though it is external from tree)."}]

commit_message:
PowerVM Driver Integration into Nova

The IBM PowerVM driver has been developed in the StackForge over the
past year.  As it has matured, this proposal seeks to integrate it into
the OpenStack Nova tree.

Implements: blueprint powervm-nova-compute-driver
Change-Id: I931b6f211c0f974f1192f154555d2c4d378cf32d

commit_message:
Add ceilometer-powervm translation domain

Since ceilometer-powervm is not in tree with ceilometer, it can't
use ceilometer's translation domain.  This change introduces i18n.py
and the ceilometer-powervm domain.

Change-Id: If8825892d506a1e0344dce888b8357910e3b7da7

commit_message:
[LBaaS v2] Validate http_method and url_path for health monitor

This change adds missing validators and unskips the related api
tests.

Also renamed unit tests that claim to check creation and updation
of a health monitor with invalid 'http_method' but do the same for
invalid 'type' instead.

Change-Id: I706f4fcf97a0793c47470e7ff8c15cd2139b57be
Closes-Bug: #1437086

commit_message:
Drop admin_role CONF dependency from cred provider

Cred providers depend on the admin_role which is read from CONF.
Adding that as a new mandatory parameter in preparation to
migration to tempest-lib.

Change-Id: Ic8ae2d36978635c9c9bade23cfef737dc3fb44b1
Partially-implements: bp tempest-library

I thought this was more a case of, now we don't need it in Nova, as we call the new method only now, we are free to remove this?"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-10-29 05:13:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

The deprecation in o.vo doesn't have anything to do with what nova does now and in liberty, so we don't need to worry about bumping the version. The version we currently require is sufficiently new to support everything we're doing.

For clarity, here is the new interface in nova:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/conductor/manager.py#L123-L132

Which takes a version manifest that is generated with this method:

https://github.com/openstack/oslo.versionedobjects/blob/master/oslo_versionedobjects/base.py#L1063-L1094

That generates a dict of object names and versions. That is called on the client side to generate that manifest, and is passed by the client to the above nova interface. So instead of the server side needing to have a mapping of every old object version and what related object versions were at that time, the client just provides a list of objects that it supports. With the static mapping, the mapping could be plain wrong (which happened a lot) or out of date, in the case of a backported fix to a stable branch.

Since we moved to making calls this way in liberty, we can now drop the old static mapping in mitaka since we don't support any clients old enough to be depending on it."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-29 08:24:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-29 08:24:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Remove obj_relationships from objects

In Liberty, we converted to using the manifest-based class
action and backport methods, which no longer rely on these
object relationship maps. They provide a full manifest of
client-side versions with each call, which is far more
robust than us trying to hand-edit these mappings (which
we get incorrect a lot).

Since we're now in Mitaka, we can drop compatibility with
clients that don't make the version-manifest calls. Those
have also been deprecated in oslo.versionedobjects.

Change-Id: Iea8b6348e3b01aaa335ec5408f07826f1e758d20

commit_message:
Add correct license for hzPasswordMatch and bi-directional check

Somewhere along the way, the license for hzPasswordMatch was
mishandled. This patch corrects  it. I am the original author of
hzPasswordMatch.

Currently, hzPasswordMatch directive does not do bi-directional check.
Meaning that the confirmation password input triggers a check on the
password input, but not vice versa. This patch makes it bi-directional.

Change-Id: Ib2907b7af7d08bb18c1f3c7daedfafccfc26c1f6
Closes-bug: #1506569
Closes-bug: #1506571

commit_message:
Add base devstack plugins support

Add support for installing nova powervm through the devstack plugins
infrastructure. This allows you to simply enable the plugin in a
devstack localrc, provide any non-default config, and run stack.sh
to configure/install it.
- Added plugin files
- Added README and example config
- Added bashate to tox test environments for scripts

Change-Id: I3dfed189e60b0aa63fc9029e3f56f2d8b7785bd3

commit_message:
Add nova-powervm translation domain

Since nova-powervm is not in tree with nova, it can't use nova's
translation domain.  This change introduces i18n.py and the
nova-powervm domain.

commit_message:
test_network_advanced_server_ops: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for 'server', 'keypair' and 'floating_ip'
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Change-Id: If1f1e78025e973110a47ad5ab3c9def761ac1af6

commit_message:
test_minimum_basic: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for 'server' and 'volume'
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Change-Id: If3917afa161cdbdd695a7fc80952f54d524d221b
Related-Bug: #1482299

commit_message:
Revert "Implement online schema migrations"

This reverts commit 2f743b2f20a559c5d2e05aa716b9137e928eb017.

At the Mitaka design summit we discussed removing this as it is
not complete, not under development, and not even an active
experiment for anyone. Since this being in the tree is confusing
people and known to be dangerous, this removes it from the tree.

Conflicts:
	nova/cmd/manage.py
	nova/db/sqlalchemy/migration.py
	nova/exception.py
	nova/tests/unit/db/test_migrations.py

Change-Id: Icae28ceee3ec975c907d73b95babab58dcb30c23

commit_message:
Add base devstack plugins support

Add support for installing ceilometer powervm through the devstack
plugins infrastructure. This allows you to simply enable the plugin
in a devstack localrc, provide any non-default config, and run
stack.sh to configure/install it.
- Added plugin files
- Added README
- Added bashate to tox test environments for scripts

Change-Id: I4f95b710026a418bda07767f1e04ddb3fd855316

commit_message:
Move nodepool.yaml from system-config to project-config

Nodepool.yaml.erb in system-config no longer contains any secrets.
Let's move it to the project-config repo.

Add the nodepool validation jobs and tox environment, initially
as non-voting until it is boot strapped.

The version of nodepool.yaml proposed matches the version in system-config
depends-on patch. A follow-up patch will be submitted with any deltas needed
when the needed-by patch is ready to merge. Until that happens, this nodepool.yaml
file won't be used and is safe to merge.

Make both gate-project-config-nodepool and gate-system-config-nodepool
non-voting to aid in bootstrapping this change.

The nodepool logging template file and associated tool that generates the file
will remain in system-config. In the short term, updates to nodepool.yaml in
this repo may require a related change in system-config to update the logging
configuration. In the longer term, nodepool will be updated to automatically
log image creations without needing a customized logging configuration.

Needed-By: I2b45a7145805368b1598d3a3e8a94f0e4eb8cf2d
Depends-On: Ib045c104daac15360e62f46e3e5683c7a387bc96
Depends-On: I89207d100eb4b6bbb502a6ed38831f49e4b29096
Change-Id: I473a1b78acdb035eb379394a7ed5f771434dc942

commit_message:
ReST API versioning support

This spec proposes a solution to report precisely ReST API versions
supported by Heat. A revision history file will be introduced to
facilitate this history maitenance and reporting.

Tags: APIImpact
Implements: blueprint rest-api-versioning
Change-Id: Icf9e42a88773e9e0eb9e146e3576be278a212172

commit_message:
Add the ability to install/enable Heat plugins

Adds the $ENABLE_HEAT_PLUGINS variable, which should be a list of
the names of the plugins the user wishes to install.

Change-Id: I2ba90002a8fad1cdce6543c89dc37c5912fe133e

[{'account_id': 18647, 'date': '2015-10-12 03:08:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-10-12 03:08:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

messages:
[{'account_id': 17869, 'date': '2015-08-12 03:23:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-08-12 03:23:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-12 03:35:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/26/211826/1/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/e266011/ : FAILURE in 1m 31s
- gate-heat-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/26/211826/1/check/gate-heat-specs-python27/7e2cc48/ : FAILURE in 1m 39s'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-08-12 04:07:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

you may want to take a look at the Senlin project:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Senlin'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-08-12 04:47:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think most of your requirements should be possible with 

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:openstack/heat+branch:master+topic:refactor-aws-asg,n,z

There is a plan to add batching create option to it in the future.'}, {'account_id': 17869, 'date': '2015-08-12 14:43:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Rabi Mishra,
One important requirement that the blueprint wanted to address is be able to request the recreation of a resource (deleting then adding) from the resource group so that it comes up with the same resource-index (that is used in properties used by workload applications). This ability is not addressed by neither Auto-scaling resource group nor by native resource group.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-08-12 16:39:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks. IMO, If the requirement is to restore a specific resource(index)(i.e maintenance of servers), as part of update/scaling, we may look at the option of improving the current blacklist functionality. i.e possibly looking at option to restore some of the indexes from blacklist during an update.

IMO, it would be better to update the spec to improve the current resources rather than adding more resources.'}, {'account_id': 17869, 'date': '2015-08-12 19:26:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Rabi Mishra,
Thanks for your comments. I agree that the option of adding requirement to your newly Autoscaling group is clearly a better option(I did not know of your work prior to writing this blueprint).
I will create a new blueprint to add the specific requirement of adding/deleting specific resources to auto scaling group. 
The new blueprint will build on top of your current work on Autoscaling group inheriting from the native resource group. I will update here with a link to the new blueprint.

I hope I will be able to contribute the to the implementation  to add the new retirement to your work.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-10-30 00:55:38.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

at request from author'}]

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-10-08 21:56:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I think most or all of the core reviewers would agree the this isn't the approach to this problem that we want in the long term, and that it would be better solved by convergence. So we should evaluate this proposal in the context of whether it is a good way to make progress in the short term while we wait for convergence phase 2.

That said, I don't think it is, for reasons I've elaborated on inline. It's not generic enough, generates even tighter coupling between the scaling group and the policy when we're trying to do the opposite, conflicts with normal use of scaling groups, can't be ported over to alternate autoscaling implementations like Senlin, appears mainly to be useful to applications for which scaling groups are wholly inappropriate anyway, and will be made completely obsolete by convergence (although we'll still have to maintain it forever).

I'd like to suggest an alternate proposal to address the same problem: an API to mark a resource as unhealthy, so that on the next stack update Heat automatically replaces it (like it already does with resources in the [CREATE|UPDATE]_FAILED state - and once phase 1 of convergence is enabled, you won't even have to wait for any in-progress updates to complete before retriggering). This could be made completely generic - it applies to any resource in any type of stack, could help solve a separate long-standing problem we've had of how to target a resource for scale-down (we'd sort unhealthy ones to the top of the queue for removing), and would remain equally relevant in the future after phase 2 of convergence lands."}, {'account_id': 17869, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:51:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

I think I do like the alternate proposal from Zane, as it covers such scenarios where the resource has actually failed(and needs to be replaced) but its status did not change yet. The proposal also allows for scale-down by the targeting a specific resource for removal.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-10-19 23:11:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I posted a spec for the alternative discussed above as Ib7ebbe0c5de3e407dbfff131c2e34c9da6537699.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-10-30 00:54:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

at request from author.'}]

I would say that it too early to consider switching to openstackclient completely and even in parts.

First, it does not still supports lots of clients and options - for example Heat itself is not part of the openstackclient yet, and other projects also do not have their complete CLI/API available in openstackclient (e.g. see the 'network' part of it [1], currently only network is supported, ports, routers, etc - no).

Besides, AFAIU other clients (like the keystone one) are deprecated in the CLI sense, with openstackclient targeting to be a single CLI client for OpenStack. For consuming the Python API, as Heat does, specific project clients are still the way to go (btw that's what openstackclient does itself).

[1] https://github.com/openstack/python-openstackclient/tree/master/openstackclient/network/v2"}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2015-09-02 06:46:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-09-02 07:13:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

IMO, we should not replace all python clients at this point (like what you said, it's too early), but I think we should use replace keystone client at this point. We only consider replace other clients once they are stable in Openstack client. At that time the keystone replacement process will be the standard process."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-02 08:11:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-02 08:13:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> but I think we should use replace keystone client at this point

Last I heard keystoneclient *CLI* was deprecated, but it was still the primary python interface, it looks like this has now changed?

https://github.com/openstack/python-openstackclient/blob/master/openstackclient/identity/client.py#L30

I'm +1 on moving to this, but I think it's probably too late/risky for Liberty at this point."}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-09-02 08:28:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
switch openstack client

we aim to replacing python-*client in heat's internal usage by
python-openstackclient.
I suggest we porting internal use of keystonclient's python API to
openstackclient at this time point.
The python-openstackclient is a uniform command structure, which will make heat
resources more manageable. There are python client (python-keystoneclient)
already deprecated in favor of python-openstackclient.

blueprint switch-openstack-client

Change-Id: I0d51a60369afb48d928e67d8f4555ac07f7a8ce4

commit_message:
Adding Job Binaries support to CLI

Adding Job Binaries commands to Sahara
OpenstackClient plugin:

$ dataprocessing job binary create
$ dataprocessing job binary list
$ dataprocessing job binary show
$ dataprocessing job binary update
$ dataprocessing job binary delete
$ dataprocessing job binary download

Partially implements: blueprint cli-as-openstackclient-plugin

Change-Id: Ia452b22ac27677a911b5b2f38a0250d4962be447

Neela, if you look back at my first comment, I made a suggestion of what you should do.  I suggested that instead of using "div" as the selector, you simply use the ID of the topology div, which is "topologyCanvasContainer".  Thus if you change your CSS selector from "div" to "#topologyCanvasContainer", only that specific div will be affected.  Right now with the way your code is, all <div> elements on the page will apply that grab cursor when moused over.  To see this, try mousing over the sub-heading of the page, "Resize the canvas by scrolling...".  You will see that your grab cursor still appears. commit_message:
Changes cursor to hand/grab in network topology.

The network topology view can get rather large and off screen.
When it gets off screen, there is no scroll bars but instead you
can grab the topology and move it around like a map. This ability
is not very clear/intuitive with the default/arrow cursor. This
patch changes the cursor in the topology view to a hand grab cursor
to make this ability more obvious and intuitive.

Closes-Bug: #1503028

Question: if we'll land convergence, so heat engine will be scallable, what is use case for waiting for resource to finish building before killing engine? Waiting for threads to finish, and call RPC other engines to continue work should be enough."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-23 10:54:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@inc0: for couple of reason, it may not be solve the problem. one, Assuming that operator wants to bring down all the engines in maintenance, in that case, its better to allow the engine to complete all of the in-progress activities. another one, also making rpc call for all of the in-progress actions would be big problem to solve than waiting for them to finish, 

Thanks for your question.'}, {'account_id': 11424, 'date': '2015-04-23 15:45:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-04-24 03:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

the api looks great, the behaviour looks asymmetrical:

 disable == complete work & sys.exit
 enable == set a flag in the db

I would have thought that the disable should not actually sys.exit() but be in a state that can be re-enabled.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:39:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Yes. you are right. Its the job of stop to do the system exit. I will update the spec as earlier.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:59:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/59/168659/8/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/e6154a9//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 01s
- gate-heat-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/59/168659/8/check/gate-heat-specs-python27/238090f/ : SUCCESS in 1m 31s'}, {'account_id': 10787, 'date': '2015-04-24 07:50:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

I will keep digging - sorry:(. If admin wants to put all engines to maintenance, he should schedule maintenance window, put all APIs down and then wait for all of engines to finish its work (since APIs are down, there will be no new scheduled tasks).

If he disables all of engines at once and keep API up, we'll end up with RPC calls piling up on queue, and incorrect messages to user, so it isn't desirable scenerio.

Putting single engine down won't require disable API as well, as I pointed out. So my question again: what real life problem it really solves?"}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-24 10:22:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Workflow-1

i discussed with inc0 in IRC and concluded our discussion to strip of the api part at this moment, from this spec and do only graceful shutdown. I will upload a new spec with this in place.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-24 10:24:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

IRC discussion link http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23heat/%23heat.2015-04-24.log'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-10-30 00:10:04.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At request from author.'}]

commit_message:
grenade-multinode: parity with ncpu jobs

We now have fixes that demonstrate the multinode grenade tests working
reasonably well. Our end game is replacing the partial-ncpu job. We
should run this non-voting job everywhere that the partial-ncpu is to
build up enough data to feel comfortable with the voting and flipping
to this job.

Depends-On: I5c899779866ebdf492d474a625eb396273bb0259

Change-Id: I4eefa772b5c9e95608a1ff4e49fc5af60bd0b1a4

commit_message:
Remove SoftDeleteMixin from NovaBase

The mixin is re-added to every class that currently inherits from
NovaBase, so there is no impact to existing classes.

The advantage is that new tables which inherit from NovaBase will not
get the mixin and won't need to have the columns for soft deletion. It
also opens the door to gradually removing the SoftDeleteMixin on a
case-by-case basis.

bp no-more-soft-delete

Change-Id: Id6b37f9a375b383f689f0e23abca7106c9872596

commit_message:
[install] Workaround for RDO lacking PyMySQL

Upstream uses the PyMySQL library in Liberty, but RDO
does not provide a package for it. Installations using
RDO packages must revert to the python-MySQL library
for any service that uses an SQL database which requires
changing the database connection string from
'mysql+pymysql://' to 'mysql://'.

As a workaround, this patch adds conditionals for each
SQL database connection string. After merging, we can
publish the RDO version of the installation guide.

Change-Id: If2423fcfbc08d028d35731aee2896a5bd45c2fb4
Implements: bp installguide-liberty
Closes-Bug: #1501991

commit_message:
Rebase on pypowervm slot_number => lpar_slot_num

Recently pypowervm refactored and expanded the slot number and LPAR ID
properties on virtual storage adapters such that
{vios|lpar}_{id|slot_num} always refers to the ID or slot number on the
VIOS or LPAR, respectively, regardless of whether you're looking at the
client or server side of the adapter.  (Change-Id:
Id626a1b23b9b2757e5e1f38fd6ed141d97fd0e74)

The only non-backward-compatible change is the renaming of slot_number
to lpar_slot_num.  This change set rebases on that modification.

Change-Id: I2d392781817b076b79cf93360588c6107dceaca4

commit_message:
Asynchronous PowerOn (spawn, rescue, unrescue)

The nova driver polls the VM state once spawn/rescue/unrescue has
completed.  It's double-duty to have those methods wait for the PowerOn
Job to complete before returning.  This change set takes advantage of
the asynchronous option on the pypowervm power_on task to allow these
methods to return as soon as the PowerOn Job has started.

Change-Id: I6c1acd172f49a7d4ec39845231a0c67329e82c11
(cherry picked from commit 39b643cbcd1ab38938d6264bf6c409491d42998a)

does not provide a package for it. Installations using
RDO packages must revert to the python-MySQL library
for any service that uses an SQL database which requires

'mysql+pymysql://' to 'mysql://'.

As a workaround, this patch adds conditionals for each
SQL database connection string. After merging, we can
publish the RDO version of the installation guide.

Implements: bp installguide-liberty
Closes-Bug: #1501991
"}]
commit_message:
[install] Workaround for RDO lacking PyMySQL

Upstream uses the PyMySQL library in Liberty, but RDO
does not provide a package for it. Installations using
RDO packages must revert to the python-MySQL library
for any service that uses an SQL database which requires
changing the database connection string from
'mysql+pymysql://' to 'mysql://'.

As a workaround, this patch adds conditionals for each
SQL database connection string. After merging, we can
publish the RDO version of the installation guide.

Change-Id: I09694c4e95643b7ad7a2a05fabf90476b01f9860
Implements: bp installguide-liberty
Closes-Bug: #1501991

commit_message:
doc: gmr: Update instructions to generate GMR error reports

Guru Meditation Reports (GMR) code in oslo.reports was recently updated
to expect SIGUSR2 as opposed to SIGUSR1, because it is reserved by
Apache 'mod_wsgi' for its own use.

So, update the Nova doc, gmr.rst, to reflect this new reality.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223133/ -- guru_meditation_report:
    Use SIGUSR2 instead of SIGUSR1

Change-Id: Iac2d606103189b965581e0c6c20b55360a04e3a6

commit_message:
Asynchronous PowerOn (spawn, rescue, unrescue)

The nova driver polls the VM state once spawn/rescue/unrescue has
completed.  It's double-duty to have those methods wait for the PowerOn
Job to complete before returning.  This change set takes advantage of
the asynchronous option on the pypowervm power_on task to allow these
methods to return as soon as the PowerOn Job has started.

Change-Id: I6c1acd172f49a7d4ec39845231a0c67329e82c11

'}, {'created': '2015-06-11 17:21:16.000000000', 'message': 'No more soft delete

There was widespread agreement at the YVR summit not to soft-delete
any more things. To remove the temptation, while cleaning up the
codebase at the same time, we should remove the SoftDeleteMixin from
NovaBase and only apply it to those models which are both soft-deleted
at some point and which are queried for deleted rows.

This means that this spec should only remove columns that Nova will not
miss. Operators will be asked to feed back on whether any of these
columns are critical to them, those which are will not be removed until
a deprecation cycle has passed.

Although this spec describes a monolithic change, implementing this in a
single review would be ambitious. The first review will remove
SoftDeleteMixin from NovaBase and reapply it everywhere. The next review
will remove it from a single candidate and so on. Once some confidence
is gained, they may be reviewed in small bundles.

blueprint no-more-soft-delete

commit_message:
No more soft delete

There was widespread agreement at the YVR summit not to soft-delete
any more things. To codify this, we should remove the SoftDeleteMixin
from NovaBase.

blueprint no-more-soft-delete

Change-Id: If9200823f472fd3e9c32a8e61f235539ec7de8a5

commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for heat

More heat configuration updates for Liberty, primarily
clarifying the extra information in the Identity service
necessary for heat operation and implementing new (lacking
documentation) configuration for Identity service access.

Change-Id: I6e4a7c182a9f9608702607995c2314dca8c4b7fa
Implements: bp installguide-liberty

The number of commands is not changed.
But ten commands order is changed.
  migration-list
  instance-action
  instance-action-list
  host-meta
  host-servers-migrate
  list-extensions
  cell-capacities
  cell-show
  host-evacuate
  host-evacuate-live

'}]
commit_message:
Update CLI reference for python-novaclient 2.33.0

The number of commands is not changed.
But ten commands order is changed.
  migration-list
  instance-action
  instance-action-list
  host-meta
  host-servers-migrate
  list-extensions
  cell-capacities
  cell-show
  host-evacuate
  host-evacuate-live

Closes-Bug: #1507851
Change-Id: Ib888b755cfcb71c4f5c0537d76e7b4cf8baaab54

commit_message:
Adding Jobs support to CLI

Adding Jobs commands to Sahara OpenstackClient
plugin:

$ dataprocessing job execute
$ dataprocessing job list
$ dataprocessing job show
$ dataprocessing job update
$ dataprocessing job delete

Partially implements: blueprint cli-as-openstackclient-plugin

Change-Id: I00cdd80740a0052d4e562276f8225378c7e8de55

I think this is an excellent simplification of the actions.  I haven't code reviewed in depth, but have a usage question.

Question:

Will this also work if we use hz-if-* directives?  Or only ng-if?"}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-09-15 18:05:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Also, is this row action specific or will work anywhere (table actions / batch actions)?'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-09-15 18:05:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ok, here are my initial thoughts:

1. This should probably work with hz-if-* as well (like hz-if-policies). This way, we can control whether the action is available if user has permission or if a certain os service is available.

2. The naming is a bit too vague for me. Context can mean a lot of things. Why not just name it row-action? Give a bunch of row-actions, generate the HTML for me. Or do you envision that we can use this for other type of actions as well?

3. Lastly, this should work in conjunction with row.actions.service.js (example https://review.openstack.org/#/c/202315/19/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/identity/static/dashboard/identity/users/table/table.row-actions.service.js) It would be perfect to iterate through the service and generate an action button. We'd need to configure how we can exclude initScope though (off topic, but we should have a base action class with initscope that other actions can DI inherit from).

Just my initial thoughts at the concept, still haven't code review yet. But this is a really good start!"}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-09-15 20:52:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-09-15 23:36:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the feedback.

Using the hz-if-* directives will be quite interesting
though I'm not very certain on how to go about it
right now.

Using the services from the row-actions services would
be quite nice.

The next patch does not have the changes from the feedback.
I'll try and address in the next."}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-09-15 23:37:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-16 00:33:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
WIP: DynamicActionList directive for dynamic actions

Actions are sensitive to user permissions
and are available based on context.
This directive allows for dynamically composing menu
actions based on how many actions are provided.

Change-Id: I4a70e141b8d3d919efd5f3ae7902d7e781a50f91
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table

commit_message:
Revert "Don't use retries for puppet deployments by default"

Instead of just setup zero retries we should give ability to
changing this parameter explicitly using web interface or fuel
cli

Related-Bug: #1510912
This reverts commit c145db34762532bf95a1d493db8e00c95db9bc67.

Change-Id: I8d3b98d66df19f070f6b06134869248a7c3d45fc

commit_message:
Fix no-share-servers CI job

Our Tempest job "*no-share-servers*" fails after merge of change [1]

The root cause for it is in changed behaviour:
After merge of change [1] share services with driver that use Nova
started verify availability of a Nova VM by its net interface and
do not report its capabilities until it is available.
It takes about 2,5 minutes. During this time scheduler has no available
hosts and we get "no hosts available" errors from it in case of CI that
runs Tempest tests much faster than 2,5 minutes after VM creation.

So, add waiter in post_test_hook.sh script.

[1] I325d6461c4b12f481769bb01f792ef850dba789c

Change-Id: I58d617dd76cf079e5e26bf6a4ddc6b4fba4e20e6
Closes-Bug: #1507605

commit_message:
Use assertTrue/False instead of assertEqual(T/F)

The usage of assertEqual(True/False, ***) should be changed to a more
meaningful format of assertTrue/False(***).

Closes-Bug: #1510001
Change-Id: Ia16af467d5f5bfca029002d9d261540947b0be92

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add ironic conductor and compute

This change introduces new node role for Ironic.

On nodes with ironic role should works following services:
* ironic-conductor
* nova-compute with ironic compute_driver
* tftp server

Partially Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic
Change-Id: I448bbf5d77723003894373bdd917ea99d58b87fd

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-28 01:30:46.000000000', 'message': 'Handle additional server options in ntp.conf

ntpd allows additional options on the server line, for example,
server ntp.example.com iburst
is a valid server line in /etc/ntp.conf. However, the previous code
would set the ntp server as "ntp.example.com iburst" which could not
be resolved

Changed the code to strip off anything on the server line after
the hostname or IP address

Change-Id: I83d9b0bdec14ac81cfd10c495dcb56cf97bff1ab

commit_message:
Handle additional server options in ntp.conf

ntpd allows additional options on the server line, for example,
server ntp.example.com iburst
is a valid server line in /etc/ntp.conf. However, the previous code
would set the ntp server as "ntp.example.com iburst" which could not
be resolved

Changed the code to strip off anything on the server line after
the hostname or IP address

Change-Id: I83d9b0bdec14ac81cfd10c495dcb56cf97bff1ab

commit_message:
libvirt detection plugin adds bad instances

Without this change, running the detection plugin results in
instances being added to /etc/monasca/agent/conf.d/libvirt.yaml that
only contained a built_by value of Libvirt. One instance would be created
for each run of the detection plugin. For example, after two runs of the
detection plugin, this would be at the end of
/etc/monasca/agent/conf.d/libvirt.yaml:

instances:
- built_by: Libvirt
- built_by: Libvirt

This doesn't actually cause any real problems with running the
libvirt detection plugin except the agent is restarted every time
the plugin is run even if there are no changes. That is because the
code thinks a new instance is being added so it has to restart the
agent.

Change-Id: Ic1a5a87b4c1c184d1e971edbb56c060dbd2473d7

Let's see what other reviewers think about it."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-10-23 22:26:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'd like to see some examples of exceptions you think are in the wrong place. This is a common source of misunderstandings, because exceptions are used for many different purposes:

User-facing exceptions (i.e. ones that can bubble up to the API) are defined in the heat.common.exceptions module.

Other exceptions are used for internal error handling, or even local flow control (think UpdateReplace). The best place for these to be defined is near the APIs that define them, and I am constantly fighting attempts to move them, inappropriately, into heat.common.exceptions.

It's possible we have some in the wrong place, but this sounds a lot like another of those attempts, except on a large scale."}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-10-29 15:27:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Centralized exceptions

I propose to centralized manage all exceptions in to an
exception folder, and categorize exceptions under exception folder. I Think
this will help us to manage exceptions, easier to find intersection of each
exceptions, and easier to inherit.

Change-Id: Ic18c3c90ed659a74fce9b8801c2b44f46a670dfb

subject: Add Ceph resources
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 4257, 'name': 'Zane Bitter', 'email': 'zbitter@redhat.com', 'username': 'zaneb'}, {'_account_id': 6899, 'name': 'Sirushti Murugesan', 'email': 'sirushtim@gmail.com', 'username': 'sirushtim'}, {'_account_id': 9760, 'name': 'koder', 'email': 'koder.mail@gmail.com', 'username': 'Kostiantyn'}, {'_account_id': 10487, 'name': 'Kanagaraj Manickam', 'email': 'mkr1481@gmail.com', 'username': 'kanagarajm'}, {'_account_id': 12404, 'name': 'Rico Lin', 'email': 'ricolin@ricolky.com', 'username': 'rico.lin'}, {'_account_id': 13009, 'name': 'Peter Razumovsky', 'email': 'prazumovsky@mirantis.com', 'username': 'prazumovsky'}, {'_account_id': 13323, 'name': 'Tetiana Lashchova', 'email': 'tlashchova@gmail.com', 'username': 'tlashchova'}, {'_account_id': 13997, 'name': 'SHIGEMATSU Mitsuhiro', 'email': 'shigematsu.mitsuhiro@lab.ntt.co.jp', 'username': 'pshige'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-07-30 03:26:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:07:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

Little typos and one comment'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:37:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:45:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:48:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

First, this seems different to what Heat generally does i.e talk to the API's   
OpenStack offers, not talk to the underlying services like Ceph for example that
it abstracts away which in this case is Cinder or Swift.                        
                                                                                
Second, could you justify why your use case can't be achieved by using the      
abstractions that SoftwareDeployment provides like for example https://github.co
m/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/ceph-storage.yaml and/or         
otherwise needs a separate resource that should exist within Heat?"}, {'account_id': 14676, 'date': '2015-07-30 10:14:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Please fix some typos.
I am wondering about the question above. At one point Swift can be replaced by Ceph but I am not sure that many users will use it directly (without Glance or Cinder). From the other point we did an exception for docker but there is interesting question: should we proceed with such exceptions for other services?'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-07-30 10:28:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 13323, 'date': '2015-07-30 11:50:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Do the new resources have any attributes? Could you please add them to the spec?'}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-07-30 12:14:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Think, you could add to nw resources description something like this:

For detailed properties depscription read `Ceph pools documentation <http://ceph.com/docs/master/rados/operations/pools/>`_

Or add to each property it's description:)"}, {'account_id': 9760, 'date': '2015-07-30 14:15:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 9760, 'date': '2015-07-30 14:15:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-30 21:13:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/82/207282/4/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/65070e9/ : FAILURE in 2m 16s
- gate-heat-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/207282/4/check/gate-heat-specs-python27/893e9e6/ : SUCCESS in 2m 10s'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-08-03 06:47:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

It can be done by software_config in some complex way (not software deploy since I have no attention to deploy ceph in this feature), but resource will be difficult to management. I kind of stuck on the same problem too, that we've done for docker as a exception resources. And should we proceed with such exceptions for other services?
I think we need more discuss for this."}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-09-08 07:10:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-09-09 12:50:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-10-23 22:26:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I don't think this is consistent with Heat's mission, which is to be an interface for users of OpenStack, not an admin interface to OpenStack. It's useful to TripleO to the extent that TripleO is a user of the OpenStack *undercloud*, but it's not Heat's job to configure the overcloud.

There are no actual dependency relations between the resources or anything, so I don't even see the value of orchestration here. If you want a declarative way to configure Ceph then that's likely the job of some configuration management tool (e.g. Puppet).

I'm not sure how an admin authenticates to Ceph to perform admin actions. Unless the answer is Keystone (and I assume it's not) then you can upgrade this review to -2."}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2015-10-29 14:58:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandon in favor of other solution for approach this resource (software config I guess).'}]

commit_message:
Fix access to vnc for multirack

Add routable networks from all nodegroups to novnc_range parameter in the firewall.

Closes-bug: #1500494

Change-Id: I2fa5394d6ba67d2d6807a5a85d271309964ff405

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

Component API implementation

Provide handler for component API with related logic.
Implement serialization format for component.

commit_message:
Allow easy neutron lbaas v2 enablement in devstack gates

There are other gates looking to go after the new lbaasv2 support
with their devstack integration tests. This patch will make it very
easy to switch to using lbassv2 while still allowing the current
lbaasv1 default.

The new lbaasv2 is not compatible and cannot be enabled with v1.
For projects that need to test with both v1 and v2, separate
devstack gate jobs will be needed.  One gate would have the
DEVSTACK_GATE_NEUTRON_LBAASV2=1 to enable the v2 support.

This is related to the heat lbaas bp
blueprint: lbaasv2-suport

Change-Id: I52c78a21258e7779de6bcb2519b2d94025ca5bd6

commit_message:
Return original interface mac

In order to prevent nailgun get inconsistent network configuration in
case of interface bonding mode return original mac address.

Change-Id: Ib0a5c86484d86bf07098a51de87baae931db66ec
Closes-Bug: #1496279
(cherry picked from commit e623c89f94911c5bc70eb73abf77921c7a5e246c)

commit_message:
api: fix default port to bind API service

Due to a wrong copy paste, the default port was 8777 which is already
used by Ceilemeter API service. Let's use the default Aodh: 8042.

Change-Id: I5b51f7337f4381035849d2f2032e1063b428540d

This reverts commit 0cd58123be5e2c2bc2f1233a3e15fb35b2ead1a0

This is a backward incompatible change that is blocking our
ability to release 2.34 for 63c7a57, which was a revert for
another backward incompatible change (2961e82) which slipped
into 2.33.

Once we release 2.34 with the bug fixes, we'll revert this

'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Remove novaclient.v1_1 module"

This reverts commit 0cd58123be5e2c2bc2f1233a3e15fb35b2ead1a0

This is a backward incompatible change that is blocking our
ability to release 2.34 for 63c7a57, which was a revert for
another backward incompatible change (2961e82) which slipped
into 2.33.

Once we release 2.34 with the bug fixes, we'll revert this
revert and release that as novaclient 3.0.

Change-Id: If79d37df3e99004897f1bb2d8564d2f1d8aa0978

commit_message:
Mock flavor_list method in tests for instances

nova.flavor_list is not mocked in the tests and
that is causing test failures in jenkins.

Closes Bug: #1511109

Change-Id: I6b9a457e103571d16dc54f94dae86c8d89feb4cb

commit_message:
Fix `raise` section in docstrings

The correct format is:
    :raises Exception: conditions

This patch fix all docstrings across the project and
add hacking rule to check it.

Change-Id: I40cc20f8d555082e284c1683522932aaa68f575c
Closes-Bug: 1470901

commit_message:
add missing timestamp to alarm_transitioned_event

Affects Patch Alarm and Update Alarm endpoints in Python API.
Fixes smoketest failure "Wrong number of history entries"
Python API passes smoketest with this correction.

Change-Id: Id94d345efc66b7754545e19ab67a8fa85996f3b6

commit_message:
Include allocated quota value in the quota reserve

When we do a quota_reserve in a project, the allocated quota for their
subprojects was not considered in the over quota calculation

Co-Authored-By: Paulo Ewerton <pauloewerton@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: Ia72e13a40e00c4ec0e986b80a7c9a322f3df659d
Closes-Bug: #1505801

commit_message:
Run after creation commands when container is up

Since we run puppet manifests inside containers when we start them, it
seems incorrect to run any *after creation commands* right after
creation and don't wait until they are up. Otherwise we may conflict
with puppet and fail. So let's use 'dockerctl' to block execution until
containers are up.

Change-Id: Icbaa0786011be30298b708404eb6db32ee3e1597
Closes-Bug: #1506810

is_deployable doesn't really give any additional information for a
release, it is removed. To make change API-backward-compatible, it is

commit_message:
Replace release.is_deployable with release.state

is_deployable doesn't really give any additional information for a
release, it is removed. To make change API-backward-compatible, it is
retained as a property dependent on release.state.

New state is added - manageonly, for environments that are not able to
be deployed, but can still be managed.

Change-Id: I518a0114730a2f227c9ef035a376f9a90d3d5bbd
Closes-bug: #1503303
DocImpact

commit_message:
Mаke possible to upgrade Fuel 7.0 to Fuel 8.0

Since we're supporting only one consequent upgrade chain, and current
master is 8.0, let's set 7.0 as previous release and unblock 7.0 -> 8.0
upgrade chain.

Change-Id: I0777ac908af45268760315329d26f4c5ce8c223a
Closes-Bug: #1506380

[{'created': '2015-10-29 12:09:30.000000000', 'message': "Remove new supervisor configs during rollback

We have to clean-up new artifacts in case of rollback and we didn't do
this for new supervisor configs. That's why upgrade fails if there were
some rollback before - we're unable to manage docker containers because
new one are launched automatically when we switched to the new
supervisor folder which is intended to be empty.

Closes-Bug: #1484091

Change-Id: Ic491d04fc3037c748b403fe0964f3fbc8db5769d
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>
"}]
commit_message:
Remove new supervisor configs during rollback

We have to clean-up new artifacts in case of rollback and we didn't do
this for new supervisor configs. That's why upgrade fails if there were
some rollback before - we're unable to manage docker containers because
new one are launched automatically when we switched to the new
supervisor folder which is intended to be empty.

Closes-Bug: #1484091

Change-Id: Ic491d04fc3037c748b403fe0964f3fbc8db5769d
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Remove new auxiliary repo in case of rollback

Since we're managing auxiliary repo in puppet manifests (creating it)
and we don't have any sort of rollback puppet manifest, we need to
clean-up its artifacts in fuel_upgrade script.

This patch removed all newly created auxiliary repo in case of
rollback.

Depends-On: Iec2645ddbee6b1b6b9e5c2816707b275542ef51b
Closes-Bug: #1480282

Change-Id: If34406dd77aed45f19fa2f352bd23a0302716053
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Change request header in HaProxy configuration for Heat API

Set requests header for Heat API service in HaProxy configuration to
'https' if ssl is used. It will help to avoid the problem with
wrong redirect during getting some info from Heat.

Cherry-picked from master. Conflicts resolved:
	deployment/puppet/openstack/manifests/ha/heat.pp
	tests/noop/spec/hosts/openstack-haproxy/openstack-haproxy-heat_spec.rb

Change-Id: Ie59c83dd6959ec66671de278764eb21d6bee1bb3
Closes-bug: #1486611

commit_message:
Adding node to group from other env is bad request

Validator was tweaked to check if node cluster is the same as node group
cluster.

Change-Id: I5021c21fce736d595c604981d8c53cf0dde495ba
Closes-bug: #1508395

commit_message:
Fix sahra-dsvm and sahara-mos jobs

The problem is sahara service type is different in MOS and dsvm.
Use api_versions context to set 'data_processing' for MOS and
'data-processig' for dsvm.

Also add missing service type 'data_processing'.

Change-Id: I4c31ec6d2dfa0b4098a0a9a647f052f935df4471

commit_message:
Added workload formulas

Workload formulas specify the concurrency and the number of iterations
for any particular test scenario based on the configuration of open stack
being tested. The first commit contains the initial versions of this
formulas. All of them scale concurrency and number of iterations
proportionally to number of controllers. These formulas need to be revised
and fine-tuned iteratively.

Also added support for basic math functions (min, max, round, ceil)
inside jinja templates.

Change-Id: I956bc3d9ff831b098cc8be3ee55283a567360906

commit_message:
Contributor Guide: Fix markup

`x` is not rendered special in any way and thus not visible. Just use
"x" instead to mark the words.

Change-Id: I51331fd2aa1ed58c55903cd0cd549b62949785c1

commit_message:
Add missing ddt class decorator

Two classes were missing the @ddt.ddt class decorator. Add it, and fix
tests where necessary.

Change-Id: I6d692a688b5d97518d7cda1736cf09f628e9cd96

commit_message:
Check gateways if non-default node groups are used

Add neutron_check_gateways to NetworkCheck class which checks that
valid gateways are specified for all networks if non-default node
groups are used.

Change-Id: I433bc322bbfa2e121fba77ea9802d4a5d3a218ad
Closes-Bug: #1472662

commit_message:
Find bridge information by network role

With network templates there is no guarantee that a bridge
named 'br-mgmt' or 'br-ex' will exist. Another bridge can
satisfy the required network roles however.

Change-Id: I85b7955dc77d0b4f30ef0b07be7d5535698b9c22
Closes-bug: #1498088
(cherry picked from commit 188ee2943fb316be1f295b608de35e7b3cd9c36a)

commit_message:
Add new project rally-ci

Single daemon that listen gerrit or other events, launch tests on
worker nodes, process and publish results.

Powered by python3 and asyncio.
Status monitoring is based on jquery and websockets.

Change-Id: Ic37d573e49383342b0d5f4d8350cd5d695f573ba

commit_message:
Format of nova-api log files was corrected

When nova-api and nova-ec2-api services are started by Apache
(it can be done with devstack config option NOVA_USE_MOD_WSGI=True)
log files contained duplication of timestamp value.

Change-Id: I5439ea8f89ca3073600456f67220e9d3f5257d97

commit_message:
policy restrain non-admin user image upload

There are some coditions exist where policy restrain the non-admin user to
update image in glance,in such conditions tempest test cases fails.

For catering this requirement new flag was introduced in tempest.conf
'image_upload_allowed' under [image] section. Its default value is true,
but in case non-admin user is not allowed to perform image upload,
value can be set to false, so that test cases are skipped rather
then getting failed.

Change-Id: Ib27e5d6c97e42bb8d2b5ee8807f928003ec73309
Closes-Bug: 1510905

commit_message:
Move endpoint_policy migrations into keystone core

This is the most basic way to move the endpoint_policy migrations into
the keystone core migrations path. Check to see if the migration was
performed already via the extension and if so skip performing it again.

Change-Id: Id1cd0143951a8086803fe739ea5f143adb1ee6ba
Implements: bp move-extensions

commit_message:
Fixed generators support in fuel plugin environment_config.yaml

Fixed attributes processing mechanism in such a way that at the first step
instance editable metadata attributes are merged with plugin attributes and
only after that the resulting attributes dict goes through generator processing

Change-Id: I4bda81f323a3f77ae5ace3927ac5f157503822ee
Closes-bug: #1473452
(cherry picked from commit d8608388bef3ea688886f6f723f8447ec5b7cbef)

commit_message:
Taken into account LACP bond configuration feature

For Ubuntu 14.04, while configuring LACP bonds should be used

     bond-slaves none

instead

     bond-slaves eth1 eth2

Change-Id: Ib98909845794ba1b1ccb0b7f07023e0d2cccd276

commit_message:
Implement some checks for lnx-bond slave interfaces

* put slave interfaces to UP state while bond assembling
* flush any IP addresses from bond slave if exists
* check 'if bond exists' while port setting up

Closes-bug: #1469746

Change-Id: I11fd2177166454e4f3f85670f30bea638adc67f9

commit_message:
Add sysctl call to set values in namespace

Set ip_nonlocal_bind in namespace explicitly to
prevent HAProxy failures at start.


Change-Id: Ibf6b2a737e97002edba2dc074c5ad239d2ef6c10
Closes-Bug: 1500871
Co-Authored-By: <dipatov@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 4aa596fd94888362e1d77b723b01609e90b5c4ae)

commit_message:
Use separate queue for agent state reports.

This optimization is needed for big clusters with hundreds
of agents where the spike of activity may trigger a burst
of RPC requests that would prevent neutron-server from processing
agent heart beats in time, triggering resource rescheduling.

This will be further optimized by running dedicated RPC workers
for state reports processing.

Related-Bug: #1496410
Change-Id: Id86a1f962aaa4f64011d57ae55d240f890cca4f7

commit_message:
Optimize interface_exists_on_bridge

Currently interface_exists_on_bridge[1] lists all files in a folder and
searchs for the file associated to the interface.

This change proposes to look for the file existence directly.

[1] neutron.plugins.ml2.drivers.linuxbridge.agent.linuxbridge_neutron_agent

Closes-Bug: #1509890
Change-Id: I23cd1edc92912b35bdc23ba0af2318b86f2cfd48

commit_message:
Log end of router updates for PD and delete branches

These execution branches call continue directly without
logging the end of the router update.  This leads to
confusion about when the last router update finishes if
it is a delete or a PD update.

Change-Id: Id82e7374aa9336e0adea3042238f30f716208373
Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>
Closes-bug: #1511004

commit_message:
Rm openstack/common/versionutils from setup.cfg

Versionutils graduated a while ago, and Nova was updated to use it in this
patch: Id0e483c662231f678bddff7ddf77cdb0b0e1a5db. This removes a reference
to openstack/common/versionutils that was missed.

Change-Id: I8d289120f99f24663537ffffe816283a98c5e511

commit_message:
Move nodepool.yaml from system-config to project-config

Nodepool.yaml.erb in system-config no longer contains any secrets.
Let's move it to the project-config repo.

Add the nodepool validation jobs and tox environment, initially
as non-voting until it is boot strapped.

The version of nodepool.yaml proposed matches the version in system-config
depends-on patch. A follow-up patch will be submitted with any deltas needed
when the needed-by patch is ready to merge. Until that happens, this nodepool.yaml
file won't be used and is safe to merge.

Make both gate-project-config-nodepool and gate-system-config-nodepool
non-voting to aid in bootstrapping this change.

The nodepool logging template file and associated tool that generates the file
will remain in system-config. In the short term, updates to nodepool.yaml in
this repo may require a related change in system-config to update the logging
configuration. In the longer term, nodepool will be updated to automatically
log image creations without needing a customized logging configuration.

Change-Id: I96fd99cf3b6a974749b92457423b1867a125b92f
Needed-By: I2b45a7145805368b1598d3a3e8a94f0e4eb8cf2d
Depends-On: Ib045c104daac15360e62f46e3e5683c7a387bc96
Depends-On: I89207d100eb4b6bbb502a6ed38831f49e4b29096

commit_message:
Remove excessive fallback iptables ACCEPT rules

The previous code was generating a fallback ACCEPT rule for every
port when there should only be one at the very end. The reason that
this wasn't causing a bug is because we have a duplicate rule remover
that was silently throwing away the extras and it happened to get them
in the right order.

Closes-Bug: #1502906
Change-Id: I83cf574f93b512be1ccefdc8da63e1783d279233

commit_message:
Removed shared instances for live-migration

Sharing instances at the class level could
cause unwanted side effects and races that would
be hard to debug/fix.

To improve code reliability, removed instance
cache from live-migration test-case.

Closes-bug:#1501040

commit_message:
Update import of oslo.config

    oslo.config module's import changes from 2.0.0
        oslo.config => oslo_config

    Without this fix, Config ref autogeneration is failed in
        import module (No module named error).

Related-Bug: #1503967

Change-Id: I68ed20e4f5b4414f5cab8e4a70234ad356b92afd

commit_message:
libvirt: add debug logging for lxc teardown paths

There are races to setup and teardown lxc-backed instances using nbd
mounts when running tempest which result in mount failing.

This change adds some debug logging to help figure out what's going on
to see where the race is happening.

Related-Bug: #1491563

Change-Id: Ief8edef0df8da1a6ee94aafa9ceaf96da5e3211b

commit_message:
WIP: No revocation event for individual tokens with persistence

In a configuration where tokens persist in some store, deleting
a token from the store is enough to revoke the token. We can
and should avoid adding a new revocation event as growing number
of revocation events causes bad performance in validation.

Change-Id: I7d53320eccd119b9ab394ddc88473d09c9b680b4

I am in direct contradiction of the premise of this patch "...but I believe in the
philosophy of providing as many config parameters as possible
directly in the classes...".  Implementing obscure parameters increases the burden of maintainability and lowers usability while providing minimal value to a small number of people.  When a person enters into our community and uses our modules they should find a clean interface that is easy to understand, not a wall of confusing parameters.

Classes should be designed as a simple interface that reduces effort and increases repeatability.  Many organization specific customizations and data lookups should be left to the profile layer and I find "nova_config" to be the right way to implement those customizations.'}, {'account_id': 9060, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:58:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I understand that perspective.  I don't totally disagree.  But I would also argue that there is already a wall of confusing parameters on many of our modules' classes.  I would rather have many parameters, with sensical defaults, that most people can ignore.  And those who want those settings have them available.

What I'm going for here is a nice clean way to have everything defined via automatic hiera data bindings, rather than having to code a bunch of nova_config stuff.

However, I suppose that's what the nova::config class is for.  Makes it a little less clean in hiera, but I could be convinced.

I guess I don't have a super strong opinion either way.  If others thing this should be abandoned, I'm fine with doing that and implementing them locally using nova::config."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-18 19:07:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-06-18 21:51:38.000000000', 'message': "Add api max limit and instance naming parameters

Adds support for the following nova.conf api settings in the
nova::api class:

  DEFAULT/osapi_max_limit
  DEFAULT/osapi_compute_unique_server_name_scope
  DEFAULT/multi_instance_display_name_template

These may be somewhat obscure settings, but I believe in the
philosophy of providing as many config parameters as possible
directly in the classes.  This allows end users to easily take
advantage of automatic data binding with hiera, etc.  Addding
these in yourself with nova::config or nova_config resources
is slightly more effort.

I'm following the de-facto convention of making class parameter
defaults match the config defaults from the upstream service.
This can be refactored to the 'undef as default' paradigm we've
discussed as that gets implemented across the board.  See:
https://etherpad.mozilla.org/liberty-summit-design-puppet-parameter-defaults

Also, I admit that this adds an egregious amount of whitespace
in the class parameters definition and nova_config section.  I'm
not opposed to different formatting, just trying to keep it
consistent.

Change-Id: I676a9fd57e97f735c431a0cdbf41293ddd68c117

commit_message:
Add api max limit and instance naming parameters

Adds support for the following nova.conf api settings in the
nova::api class:

  DEFAULT/osapi_max_limit
  DEFAULT/osapi_compute_unique_server_name_scope
  DEFAULT/multi_instance_display_name_template

These may be somewhat obscure settings, but I believe in the
philosophy of providing as many config parameters as possible
directly in the classes.  This allows end users to easily take
advantage of automatic data binding with hiera, etc.  Addding
these in yourself with nova::config or nova_config resources
is slightly more effort.

I'm following the de-facto convention of making class parameter
defaults match the config defaults from the upstream service.
This can be refactored to the 'undef as default' paradigm we've
discussed as that gets implemented across the board.  See:
https://etherpad.mozilla.org/liberty-summit-design-puppet-parameter-defaults

Also, I admit that this adds an egregious amount of whitespace
in the class parameters definition and nova_config section.  I'm
not opposed to different formatting, just trying to keep it
consistent.

commit_message:
always set upgrade_level to auto

The partial-ncpu job needed to do a very special dance to set, only on
the partial-ncpu jobs, the upgrade_level, before the new side comes
up.

Now that nova supports the 'auto' stanza, we should just set it all
the time on upgrade. Nodes that get upgraded will know to be auto,
nodes that are not will end up using their normal default latest.

Depends-On: Ieb92f52180369f2513bda40dcbaa9db392816841

Change-Id: I5c899779866ebdf492d474a625eb396273bb0259

commit_message:
grenade-multinode: don't set upgrade level initially

In Nova, services talk the latest version of RPC, unless you tell them
otherwise. This can be set with the upgrade_level config option.

You are supposed to set this *before* upgrade, not *before* initial
installation. While this happened to work in the kilo case, it was the
wrong place to do it. Grenade itself will be responsible for setting
this at the correct time in I5c899779866ebdf492d474a625eb396273bb0259
and devstack-gate should not be in the business of touching this.

Change-Id: Ieb92f52180369f2513bda40dcbaa9db392816841

commit_message:
Pre-stage boot.ipxe into /httpboot

Ironic only deploys the boot.ipxe script when a host is
prepared for deployment. Due to this, test jobs utilizing
a feature such as inspection, cannot boot test nodes.

Change-Id: I67409203f0a01f14c3f3a88cd72c87b960542059

commit_message:
Unlimited option max_resources_per_stack

Since biggest issue for memory problems is nested stack max
resources validation, this patch creates option to remove limit
which skips whole validation whatsoever.

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/resources/stack_resource.py
	heat/tests/engine/test_stack_create.py

Cherry-picked from heat: 601a45d2c9c8d812c841bd47d3abf4a206467fd9
Related-Bug: #1455589
Change-Id: I7c851fcad2d4a41b2f9df42244862b04304812b0

commit_message:
Change assertTrue(isinstance()) by optimal assert

Some of tests use different method of assertTrue(isinstance(A, B)) or
assertEqual(type(A), B). The correct way is to use assertIsInstance(A,
B) provided by testtools.

Change-Id: I2ce6f9afeaf2c55fb781d3ba397cb8f7cbf8b686

instead of:

commit_message:
Use assert(Not)In instead of assertTrue/False

Neutron tests should use:

self.assertIn(value, list) and
self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

self.assertTrue(value in list) and
self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
>>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
>>> AssertionError: False is not true

To enforce this improvement, this patch is created.

Change-Id: I4a05ad5a5ff9674dd94cff8b11585fd39dc264b3
Related-Bug: #1218713
